{"id":123078,"global_id":"Z2lkOi8vaGFja2Vyb25lL1JlcG9ydC8xMjMwNzg=","url":"https://hackerone.com/reports/123078","title":"https://rpm.newrelic.com/login vulnerable to host header attack","state":"Closed","substate":"resolved","readable_substate":"Resolved","created_at":"2016-03-14T20:36:09.615Z","submitted_at":"2016-03-14T20:36:09.615Z","is_member_of_team?":false,"reporter":{"disabled":false,"username":"geeknik","url":"/geeknik","profile_picture_urls":{"small":"https://profile-photos.hackerone-user-content.com/variants/7xfGZCKCxUuGLYGfuUZM3XyY/3afcb5c896247e7ee8ada31b1c1eb8657e22241f911093acfe4ec7e97a3a959a"},"is_me?":false,"cleared":true,"hackerone_triager":false,"hacker_mediation":false},"team":{"id":17011,"url":"https://hackerone.com/newrelic","handle":"newrelic","profile_picture_urls":{"small":"https://profile-photos.hackerone-user-content.com/variants/000/017/011/eba06abb23bd6c9c7d719ddafb9fa83bd2d66aaa_original./3afcb5c896247e7ee8ada31b1c1eb8657e22241f911093acfe4ec7e97a3a959a","medium":"https://profile-photos.hackerone-user-content.com/variants/000/017/011/eba06abb23bd6c9c7d719ddafb9fa83bd2d66aaa_original./eb31823a4cc9f6b6bb4db930ffdf512533928a68a4255fb50a83180281a60da5"},"permissions":[],"submission_state":"open","default_currency":"usd","awards_miles":false,"offers_bounties":true,"state":"public_mode","only_cleared_hackers":false,"profile":{"name":"New Relic","twitter_handle":"newrelic","website":"https://newrelic.com","about":"New Relic's Coordinated Disclosure Program"}},"has_bounty?":false,"in_validation?":false,"rejected_anc_report_that_can_be_sent_back_to_anc_triagers?":false,"can_view_team":true,"can_view_report":true,"is_external_bug":false,"is_published":false,"is_participant":false,"stage":4,"public":true,"visibility":"full","cve_ids":[],"singular_disclosure_disabled":false,"disclosed_at":"2017-03-20T01:40:06.482Z","bug_reporter_agreed_on_going_public_at":null,"team_member_agreed_on_going_public_at":"2017-02-18T01:39:48.397Z","comments_closed?":false,"facebook_team?":false,"team_private?":false,"vulnerability_information":"It appears that https://rpm.newrelic.com/login is vulnerable to a host header attack flaw whereas the HTTP Host header can be controlled by a malicious user.\n\nPOC:\n```\ncurl -H \"Host: rpm.newrelic.com\" -H \"X-Forwarded-Host: geeknik.com\" https://rpm.newrelic.com/login\n```\n\nResult:\n```\n\u003chtml\u003e\u003cbody\u003eYou are being \u003ca href=\"https://geeknik.com/auth/newrelic?origin=%2Flogin\"\u003eredirected\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/body\u003e\u003c/html\u003e\n```\n\nAs you can see here, if the malicious user controls the HTTP Host header, they can redirect users to a malicious login page where their credentials could potentially be captured. Granted, this is an edge case, but it is still an issue where malicious users can cause your web application(s) to behave in unexpected ways. \n\nThe web application should use the SERVER_NAME instead of the Host header. It should also create a dummy vhost that catches all requests with unrecognized Host headers. This can also be done under Nginx by specifying a non-wildcard SERVER_NAME.","vulnerability_information_html":"\u003cp\u003eIt appears that \u003ca title=\"https://rpm.newrelic.com/login\" href=\"/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Frpm.newrelic.com%2Flogin\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\"\u003e\u003cspan\u003ehttps://rpm.newrelic.com/login\u003c/span\u003e\u003ci class=\"icon-external-link\"\u003e\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/a\u003e is vulnerable to a host header attack flaw whereas the HTTP Host header can be controlled by a malicious user.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003ePOC:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"highlight\"\u003e\u003cpre class=\"highlight plaintext\"\u003e\u003ccode\u003ecurl -H \u0026quot;Host: rpm.newrelic.com\u0026quot; -H \u0026quot;X-Forwarded-Host: geeknik.com\u0026quot; https://rpm.newrelic.com/login\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eResult:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"highlight\"\u003e\u003cpre class=\"highlight html\"\u003e\u003ccode\u003e\u003cspan class=\"nt\"\u003e\u0026lt;html\u0026gt;\u0026lt;body\u0026gt;\u003c/span\u003eYou are being \u003cspan class=\"nt\"\u003e\u0026lt;a\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan class=\"na\"\u003ehref=\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan class=\"s\"\u003e\u0026quot;https://geeknik.com/auth/newrelic?origin=%2Flogin\u0026quot;\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan class=\"nt\"\u003e\u0026gt;\u003c/span\u003eredirected\u003cspan class=\"nt\"\u003e\u0026lt;/a\u0026gt;\u003c/span\u003e.\u003cspan class=\"nt\"\u003e\u0026lt;/body\u0026gt;\u0026lt;/html\u0026gt;\u003c/span\u003e\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAs you can see here, if the malicious user controls the HTTP Host header, they can redirect users to a malicious login page where their credentials could potentially be captured. Granted, this is an edge case, but it is still an issue where malicious users can cause your web application(s) to behave in unexpected ways. \u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe web application should use the SERVER_NAME instead of the Host header. It should also create a dummy vhost that catches all requests with unrecognized Host headers. This can also be done under Nginx by specifying a non-wildcard SERVER_NAME.\u003c/p\u003e\n","weakness":{"id":53,"name":"Open Redirect"},"original_report_id":null,"original_report_url":null,"attachments":[],"allow_singular_disclosure_at":"2017-03-20T01:39:48.435Z","allow_singular_disclosure_after":-119241680.77039678,"singular_disclosure_allowed":true,"vote_count":8,"voters":["delimitry","eveeez","geeknik","r3y","spetr0x","atik-rahman","dyabla","adsence771"],"structured_scope":null,"abilities":{"assignable_team_members":[],"assignable_team_member_groups":[]},"can_edit_custom_fields_attributes":false,"activities":[{"id":839713,"is_internal":false,"editable":false,"type":"Activities::Comment","message":"Thanks for this report ! We've seen this issue before via scanning tools although this is the first time it's been reported via HackerOne. We've previously considered it a very low severity issue since an attacker would have to MITM the HTTPS connection to our servers to inject a malicious host header. We're eager to make sure we haven't missed any other attack vectors - do you have any suggestions for other ways an attacker could inject a malicious header assuming the site is using HTTPS ? ","markdown_message":"\u003cp\u003eThanks for this report ! We\u0026#39;ve seen this issue before via scanning tools although this is the first time it\u0026#39;s been reported via HackerOne. We\u0026#39;ve previously considered it a very low severity issue since an attacker would have to MITM the HTTPS connection to our servers to inject a malicious host header. We\u0026#39;re eager to make sure we haven\u0026#39;t missed any other attack vectors - do you have any suggestions for other ways an attacker could inject a malicious header assuming the site is using HTTPS ? \u003c/p\u003e\n","automated_response":false,"created_at":"2016-03-15T00:04:10.470Z","updated_at":"2016-03-15T00:04:10.470Z","actor":{"username":"imelven","cleared":false,"url":"/imelven","profile_picture_urls":{"medium":"https://profile-photos.hackerone-user-content.com/variants/000/036/153/809e507ea6cd7c5c120920d1d4ce70336974d422_original.jpeg/eb31823a4cc9f6b6bb4db930ffdf512533928a68a4255fb50a83180281a60da5"},"hackerone_triager":false,"hackerone_employee":false},"genius_execution_id":null,"team_handle":"newrelic","actor_is_team_member":false,"actor_is_concealed_member":false},{"id":839714,"is_internal":false,"editable":false,"type":"Activities::BugTriaged","message":"","markdown_message":"","automated_response":false,"created_at":"2016-03-15T00:04:23.385Z","updated_at":"2016-03-15T00:04:23.385Z","actor":{"username":"imelven","cleared":false,"url":"/imelven","profile_picture_urls":{"medium":"https://profile-photos.hackerone-user-content.com/variants/000/036/153/809e507ea6cd7c5c120920d1d4ce70336974d422_original.jpeg/eb31823a4cc9f6b6bb4db930ffdf512533928a68a4255fb50a83180281a60da5"},"hackerone_triager":false,"hackerone_employee":false},"genius_execution_id":null,"team_handle":"newrelic","actor_is_team_member":false,"actor_is_concealed_member":false},{"id":839750,"is_internal":false,"editable":false,"type":"Activities::Comment","message":"To be fair, it would take time and effort to leverage this attack using a MITM proxy in San Francisco outside of places that I know use your services. Maybe I'd capture 1 or 100 logins, it is hard to say really. I'm not seeing an SQLi or XSS flaw in the host header, so that's a plus. \n\nOther subdomains suffer from this as well:\n```\ncurl -H \"Host: 127.0.01\" https://api.newrelic.com/\n\u003chtml\u003e\u003cbody\u003eYou are being \u003ca href=\"https://127.0.01/login?return_to=%2F\"\u003eredirected\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/body\u003e\u003c/html\u003e\n```\n\n```\ncurl -H \"Host: 127.0.01\" https://alerts.newrelic.com\n\u003chtml\u003e\u003cbody\u003eYou are being \u003ca href=\"https://127.0.01/auth/newrelic?origin=%2F\"\u003eredirected\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/body\u003e\u003c/html\u003e\n```\n\n```\ncurl -H \"Host: 127.0.01\" https://login.newrelic.com\n\u003chtml\u003e\u003cbody\u003eYou are being \u003ca href=\"https://127.0.01/login\"\u003eredirected\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/body\u003e\u003c/html\u003e\n```\n\nBeyond that, I really don't have much more to share on how this might be exploitable in other ways. I'm sure you'll get plenty of reports about this though. ;)\n","markdown_message":"\u003cp\u003eTo be fair, it would take time and effort to leverage this attack using a MITM proxy in San Francisco outside of places that I know use your services. Maybe I\u0026#39;d capture 1 or 100 logins, it is hard to say really. I\u0026#39;m not seeing an SQLi or XSS flaw in the host header, so that\u0026#39;s a plus. \u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eOther subdomains suffer from this as well:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"highligh